words.meaning: To invent (a new word or phrase).
examples: He is credited with coining the term 'cyberspace'.
She was known for coining clever phrases to describe complex ideas.

words.meaning: A loss of nerve or confidence.
examples: He got cold feet just before the wedding and called it off.
She was going to try bungee jumping but got cold feet at the last minute.

words.meaning: A show of intentional unfriendliness; a slight or rejection.
examples: After their argument, she gave him the cold shoulder for a week.
I tried to be friendly, but he just gave me the cold shoulder.

words.meaning: To work jointly on an activity, especially to produce or create something.
examples: The two artists decided to collaborate on a mural.
Scientists from different countries collaborated on the research project.

words.meaning: A piece of art made by sticking various different materials such as photographs and pieces of paper or fabric onto a backing.
examples: She made a collage of her favorite family photos.
The art class project was to create a collage representing their dreams.

words.meaning: To cooperate in a secret or unlawful way in order to deceive or gain an advantage over others.
examples: The companies were accused of colluding to fix prices.
Several officials colluded to embezzle public funds.

words.meaning: Secret or illegal cooperation or conspiracy, especially in order to cheat or deceive others.
examples: The investigation uncovered collusion between the two companies.
He was found guilty of acting in collusion with the enemy.

words.meaning: To influence, especially in a negative way; to misrepresent.
examples: His personal biases colored his judgment of the situation.
The media's reporting colored the public's perception of the event.

words.meaning: Extremely large; enormous.
examples: The ancient Egyptians built colossal pyramids.
It was a colossal waste of money.

words.meaning: (Typically of a woman) pleasant to look at; attractive.
examples: The painting depicted a comely young maiden.
He was struck by her comely face and graceful manner.

words.meaning: Courtesy and considerate behavior toward others; mutual respect among nations.
examples: The two leaders treated each other with comity and respect.
The principle of comity requires courts in one country to respect the laws of another.

words.meaning: To begin; to start.
examples: The graduation ceremony will commence at 10:00 AM.
They will commence building the new bridge next year.

words.meaning: Deserving praise.
examples: Her dedication to her work is commendable.
His effort to help the poor was a commendable act.

words.meaning: Corresponding in size or degree; in proportion.
examples: Your salary will be commensurate with your experience.
The punishment should be commensurate with the crime.

words.meaning: A person who comments on events or on a text.
examples: The sports commentator provided an exciting play-by-play of the game.
Political commentators offered their analysis of the election results.

words.meaning: To express or feel sympathy or pity; sympathize.
examples: She commiserated with her friend on the loss of her job.
The players commiserated with each other after the tough defeat.

words.meaning: Roomy and comfortable.
examples: They moved into a commodious house with a large backyard.
The commodious armchair was perfect for reading.

words.meaning: Friendly and sociable.
examples: They spent a companionable evening chatting by the fire.
He was a quiet but companionable travel partner.

words.meaning: Sympathetic pity and concern for the sufferings or misfortunes of others.
examples: She showed great compassion for the homeless.
His heart was filled with compassion for the victims of the disaster.

words.meaning: (Of two things) able to exist or occur together without conflict.
examples: The new software is not compatible with older operating systems.
Their personalities are not compatible, so they argue a lot.

words.meaning: Evoking interest, attention, or admiration in a powerfully irresistible way.
examples: The book was so compelling that I couldn't put it down.
There is compelling evidence that he is guilty.

words.meaning: A collection of concise but detailed information about a particular subject, especially in a book or other publication.
examples: The book is a compendium of knowledge about the ancient world.
He published a compendium of his life's work.

words.meaning: Reducing or offsetting the unwelcome effects of something by exerting an opposite force or effect.
examples: The court awarded compensatory damages to the victim.
He received a compensatory day off for working on the weekend.

words.meaning: Having the necessary ability, knowledge, or skill to do something successfully.
examples: She is a highly competent lawyer.
We need a competent person to manage the project.

words.meaning: Showing smug or uncritical satisfaction with oneself or one's achievements.
examples: After their initial success, the team became complacent and lost the next game.
We can't afford to be complacent about the threat of climate change.

words.meaning: The quality of being willing to please others; agreeableness.
examples: Her complaisance made her popular, but it also meant she was easily taken advantage of.
He showed an excessive complaisance to his boss's every demand.

words.meaning: Willing to please others; obliging; agreeable.
examples: The complaisant waiter was happy to accommodate our special requests.
She was too complaisant to stand up for her own rights.

words.meaning: A thing that completes or brings to perfection.
examples: The wine is a perfect complement to the cheese.
His skills are a good complement to the team.

words.meaning: Combining in such a way as to enhance or emphasize the qualities of each other or another.
examples: The two colors are complementary and look great together.
They have complementary skills that make them a good team.

words.meaning: Inclined to agree with others or obey rules, especially to an excessive degree; acquiescent.
examples: The company was found to be compliant with all safety regulations.
He has a very compliant and obedient personality.

words.meaning: Involved with others in an illegal activity or wrongdoing.
examples: He was complicit in the cover-up of the scandal.
She was found to be complicit in her husband's crimes.

words.meaning: The state of being involved with others in an illegal activity or wrongdoing.
examples: Her complicity in the crime could not be denied.
The investigation revealed the complicity of several high-ranking officials.

words.meaning: To act in accordance with a wish or command.
examples: You must comply with the rules or you will be asked to leave.
He refused to comply with the officer's request.

words.meaning: A part or element of a larger whole, especially a part of a machine or vehicle.
examples: The computer is made up of many different components.
Trust is a vital component of any healthy relationship.

words.meaning: The state or feeling of being calm and in control of oneself.
examples: Despite the chaos, she maintained her composure.
He lost his composure and started shouting.

words.meaning: To make (something bad) worse; intensify the negative aspects of.
examples: His refusal to apologize only compounded the problem.
The rain compounded the difficulties of the rescue mission.

words.meaning: Complete; including all or nearly all elements or aspects of something.
examples: The book provides a comprehensive overview of the subject.
The company offers a comprehensive benefits package.

words.meaning: An agreement or a settlement of a dispute that is reached by each side making concessions.
examples: After a long negotiation, they finally reached a compromise.
In any relationship, you have to be willing to compromise.

words.meaning: A feeling of guilt or moral scruple that prevents or follows the doing of something bad.
examples: He felt no compunction about lying to his friends.
She had some compunction about borrowing the money without asking.

words.meaning: Having an outline or surface that curves inward like the interior of a circle or sphere.
examples: A spoon has a concave shape.
The cave had a concave roof that arched overhead.

words.meaning: To admit that something is true or valid after first denying or resisting it.
examples: After losing the election, the candidate conceded defeat.
He was forced to concede that his argument was flawed.

words.meaning: Excessive pride in oneself; vanity.
examples: His conceit was so great that he couldn't see his own faults.
She was full of conceit about her good looks.

words.meaning: A thing that is granted, especially in response to demands; a thing conceded.
examples: The company made several concessions to the striking workers.
As a concession, he agreed to work on Saturday.

words.meaning: To stop (someone) from being angry or discontented; placate; pacify.
examples: He tried to conciliate his angry neighbor by offering to pay for the broken window.
The government attempted to conciliate the protesters with promises of reform.

words.meaning: Intended or likely to placate or pacify.
examples: He spoke in a conciliatory tone, hoping to calm the situation.
The company made a conciliatory gesture by offering a full refund.

words.meaning: (Of evidence or argument) serving to prove a case; decisive.
examples: The DNA evidence was conclusive proof of his guilt.
The study provided conclusive evidence that the new drug was effective.

words.meaning: To create or devise (a story or plan).
examples: He concocted a wild story to explain his absence.
The prisoners concocted a plan to escape.

words.meaning: Naturally accompanying or associated.
examples: Loss of appetite is a concomitant effect of the medication.
War and its concomitant suffering have plagued humanity for centuries.

words.meaning: Agreement or harmony between people or groups.
examples: The two nations lived in concord for many years.
The family dinner was a rare moment of concord.

words.meaning: Strong sexual desire; lust.
examples: The novel explores themes of concupiscence and spiritual redemption.
He struggled to control his concupiscence.

words.meaning: To be of the same opinion; to agree.
examples: I concur with the previous speaker's assessment.
The two experts concurred on the cause of the problem.

words.meaning: To express complete disapproval of, typically in public; to censure.
examples: The international community condemned the country's actions.
The building was condemned as unsafe.

words.meaning: To show feelings of superiority; to be patronizing.
examples: He would often condescend to his employees, making them feel inferior.
She condescended to explain the simple instructions to me.

words.meaning: (Of punishment or retribution) appropriate to the crime or wrongdoing; fitting and deserved.
examples: The villain in the movie received his condign punishment in the end.
The public demanded a condign sentence for the perpetrator.

words.meaning: An expression of sympathy, especially on the occasion of a death.
examples: He offered his condolences to the grieving family.
The president sent a message of condolence to the victims' families.

words.meaning: To accept and allow (behavior that is considered morally wrong or offensive) to continue.
examples: The school does not condone bullying in any form.
By not speaking out, you are condoning his bad behavior.

words.meaning: Third-person singular present tense of condone; accepts or allows wrong behavior.
examples: The coach never condones cheating among his players.
A society that condones violence will ultimately suffer.

words.meaning: Making a certain situation or outcome likely or possible.
examples: The quiet library was conducive to studying.
A positive attitude is conducive to success.

words.meaning: Having the property of conducting heat or electricity.
examples: Metal is a conductive material.
Water is conductive, so you should not use electrical appliances near it.

words.meaning: To grant or bestow (a title, degree, benefit, or right); to have discussions; exchange opinions.
examples: The university will confer degrees on the graduating students.
The president will confer with his advisors before making a decision.
